  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What does rhodiola rosea do?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Rhodiola rosea is a classified adaptogen — a botanical that helps the body resist and adapt to physical, mental, and environmental stressors. Its primary active compounds (rosavins and salidroside) modulate the stress response by influencing the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis and key neurotransmitter systems. Rhodiola inhibits the enzyme monoamine oxidase (MAO), slowing the breakdown of serotonin, dopamine, and norepinephrine — neurotransmitters critical for mood, motivation, and mental energy. Rhodiola also modulates cortisol release, preventing the excessive cortisol spikes that cause fatigue, brain fog, and burnout during chronic stress. Clinical trials have demonstrated that rhodiola reduces mental fatigue, improves cognitive performance under stress, enhances physical endurance, and reduces symptoms of burnout and mild-to-moderate depression.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much rhodiola should I take?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Clinical trials have used rhodiola rosea extract at 200-600mg daily, standardized to 3% rosavins and 1% salidroside (the standard SHR-5 extract ratio). For fatigue and mental performance: 200-400mg daily is effective. For stress adaptation and burnout: 400-600mg daily. For exercise performance: 200mg taken 1 hour before exercise. Most experts recommend starting at 200mg and increasing to 400-600mg based on individual response. Rhodiola is best taken in the morning or early afternoon — its energizing effects can interfere with sleep if taken too late in the day. Effects are typically noticed within 1-3 weeks of daily use, with optimal results at 4-8 weeks.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Is rhodiola better than ashwagandha?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Rhodiola and ashwagandha are both adaptogens but serve different primary purposes. Rhodiola is energizing and performance-enhancing — best for fatigue, mental performance, focus, and daytime energy. It modulates dopamine and norepinephrine (stimulating neurotransmitters). Ashwagandha is calming and recovery-promoting — best for anxiety, sleep quality, cortisol reduction, and nighttime relaxation. It primarily modulates GABA and cortisol (calming systems). The choice depends on your primary need: if you struggle with fatigue, brain fog, and low motivation, rhodiola is more appropriate. If you struggle with anxiety, poor sleep, and chronic stress, ashwagandha is more appropriate. Many people use rhodiola in the morning and ashwagandha in the evening for complementary adaptogenic support throughout the day.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does rhodiola help with depression?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Clinical evidence supports rhodiola for mild-to-moderate depression. A 2015 randomized controlled trial published in Phytomedicine compared rhodiola extract (340mg/day and 680mg/day) to the antidepressant sertraline (50mg/day). Rhodiola produced a smaller antidepressant effect than sertraline but with significantly fewer side effects and better tolerability. Both rhodiola doses improved depression scores significantly compared to baseline. The mechanism involves MAO inhibition (preserving serotonin and dopamine) and modulation of stress-related cortisol that contributes to depressive symptoms. Rhodiola is not a replacement for prescribed antidepressants in moderate-to-severe depression, but represents an evidence-backed option for mild depressive symptoms, particularly when fatigue and low motivation are prominent features.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can I take rhodiola every day?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. Clinical trials have used daily rhodiola supplementation for up to 12 weeks without significant adverse effects. The traditional use of rhodiola in Scandinavian and Russian folk medicine spans centuries of daily consumption. Some practitioners recommend cycling rhodiola (5 days on, 2 days off, or 6 weeks on, 2 weeks off) to prevent potential tolerance development, though clinical evidence for tolerance is limited. Rhodiola should be taken in the morning or early afternoon — its energizing effects on dopamine and norepinephrine can interfere with sleep if taken in the evening. Start with the lowest effective dose (200mg) and increase based on your response. Daily use for at least 4-8 weeks is recommended to fully assess effectiveness.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What should I look for in rhodiola supplements?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The most important quality marker is standardization to 3% rosavins and 1% salidroside — the ratio found in the SHR-5 extract used in the majority of clinical trials. This 3:1 rosavin-to-salidroside ratio mirrors the natural ratio found in Rhodiola rosea root and has the most clinical evidence supporting its efficacy. Avoid products that standardize only to salidroside or provide generic "rhodiola extract" without standardization — these may not contain adequate rosavins. Look for third-party testing (USP, NSF, TRU-ID) to confirm botanical identity (many rhodiola supplements have been found to contain other Rhodiola species, not the clinically studied R. rosea). The dose should be 200-600mg of standardized extract per serving.' } },
] };
